# AI Gateway Architecture

## Core Concept

The gateway sits between clients and LLM providers. Clients send standardized requests; the gateway selects a provider, executes the call, and returns a normalized response.

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    Client --> Gateway[AI Gateway API]
    Gateway --> Router[Provider Router]
    Router --> Ollama[Ollama]
    Router --> OpenAI[OpenAI]
    Router --> Anthropic[Anthropic]
    Router --> Others[Gemini / Azure / Bedrock]
```

## Provider Abstraction

All providers implement `BaseLLMService` (`services/base_llm.py`):

```python
class BaseLLMService(ABC):
    async def chat(self, message: str) -> ...: ...
    async def check_connection(self) -> dict: ...
```

Current implementation: `OllamaService`. Future providers add a new class + registry entry — no route changes.

## Target Provider Support

| Provider | Status |
|----------|--------|
| Ollama | Implemented |
| OpenAI | Planned |
| Anthropic | Planned |
| Gemini | Planned |
| Azure OpenAI | Planned |
| AWS Bedrock | Planned |

Adding a provider should require: one service class, config vars, enum entry, and DI registration.

## Layer Flow

```
HTTP Request
  → Middleware (RequestID, Timing)
  → Route (api/routes/)
  → Service (services/)
  → Provider (OllamaService, etc.)
  → Normalized APIResponse
```

Routes never import provider SDKs directly.

## Future Gateway Capabilities

Designed to support (not yet built):

- Model registry and routing engine
- Streaming responses
- Embeddings, vision, function calling
- RAG (Qdrant), caching (Redis), agents, workflows
- Authentication, rate limiting, observability

## Naming

- Use "AI Gateway" in docs, OpenAPI description, and user-facing text
- Avoid "chatbot" or "coding assistant" — this is infrastructure, not an end-user product

## Configuration

Provider settings belong in `core/config.py` (or future provider-specific config modules). Secrets via environment variables only.
